\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
In general, a statement involving the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},x_{2},\dots,x_{n}$
\end_inset

 can be denoted by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P\left(x_{1},x_{2},\dots,x_{n}\right).
\]

\end_inset

A statement of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(x_{1},x_{2},\dots,x_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the value of the 
\emph on
propositional function 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 
\emph default
at the 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-tuple 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(x_{1},x_{2},\dots,x_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 is also called an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-place predicate or a 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

-ary (from -ary as in binary, ternary) predicate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

